2. Subagents / Agent-to-Agent — Delegation patterns
Claude Code can spawn subagents to run parallel or specialized tasks. Best practices:

Use Task tool calls to delegate bounded, well-defined subtasks
Keep subagent prompts narrow and specific — they don't need the full context, just what's relevant to their job
Subagents work best for: file operations, research tasks, code generation in isolated modules, testing

Pattern to internalize:
Orchestrator Claude → defines the plan, manages state
  └── Subagent A → handles data fetching
  └── Subagent B → handles code generation
  └── Subagent C → handles validation/testing

3. Skills / CLAUDE.md — Persistent instructions & context injection
This is the most underutilized lever. Think of it as your standard operating procedures for Claude Code.
CLAUDE.md (project-level):

Lives in your repo root
Claude Code reads it automatically at session start
Put in: project overview, tech stack, naming conventions, preferred patterns, "never do X"

~/.claude/CLAUDE.md (global):

Applies to every Claude Code session
Put in: your personal preferences, common tools you use, your environment details

What to put in them:
markdown# Project: myDREAMS
## Stack: Python, SQLite, FastAPI, PropStream API
## Conventions: snake_case, typed functions, docstrings required
## Never: use pandas when raw SQL suffices
## MCP context: sqlite MCP is connected, use it for all DB queries
## Preferred patterns: repository pattern for data access

Practical Workflow for Maximizing Results
Before starting a task:

Ask yourself: does this task need live data (MCP) or domain knowledge (CLAUDE.md context)?
Make sure relevant MCPs are connected
Have a CLAUDE.md that describes the current project state

During a task:

Use /mcp to verify what's connected
Explicitly tell Claude Code which tools to use: "Use the sqlite MCP to query the leads table" beats hoping it figures it out
For complex tasks, ask Claude to write the plan first before executing — this is where you catch bad assumptions cheap

Skill building over time:

Every time you solve a repeatable problem, distill the pattern into CLAUDE.md
Treat it like a growing runbook


Honest Gaps to Know

MCP ecosystem is still maturing — quality varies wildly; vet before trusting
Agent-to-agent coordination can get expensive token-wise; don't over-decompose simple tasks
CLAUDE.md doesn't version-control itself by default — worth committing it intentionally

